A taxi driver, who allegedly hit a large group of students in Port Elizabeth at the weekend with his taxi killing three, could be on the run to his home country.Today police released an image of Brighton Tsvipa, 30, who abandoned the damaged taxi near his home in Missionvale after the accident on Sunday morning.Captain Andre Beetge says he appeasers' to be in the country illegally.The taxi owner assisted police with a copy of Tsvipa&rsquo;s passport."We are still looking for him. If the public see this guy, they must immediately phone police," said Beetge.There is also a possibility that he could slip out of the country illegally.A huge crowd of teenagers mixed with young adults, had been celebrating the end of exams and the start of school holidays in front of Eyethu nightclub, in Kwazakhele, in the early hours of Sunday morning.It is believed that hundreds of people were at the celebration, drinking alcohol and that they had used a bunch of taxis to block the road off so they could party.Beetge said a white minibus drove through the crowd at quite a speed around 01:30.Yonela Matyu, 14, Siyasanga Adoni, 19, and Mngomezulu Nokulunga, 14, were killed.Police confirmed that liquor officers were investigating whether all alcohol vendors in the area were adhering to the liquor act.http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/border-posts-on-alert-for-pe-taxi-driver-who-allegedly-killed-3-teens-20170704